      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Why Intact Proteins Are Absent\n\nProtein–metal equilibria are inherently difficult to characterize with classical stability constants because:\n\n1. **Multiple binding sites** with different affinities (e.g., transferrin has two Fe³⁺ sites with log K ~20–22)\n2. **Synergistic anion requirements** (transferrin needs carbonate/bicarbonate as a co-ligand)\n3. **Conformational changes** upon metal binding that alter the equilibrium model\n4. **Conditional constants** that depend heavily on pH, making simple β definitions problematic",
        "claims": [
          {
            "start": 0,
            "end": 34,
            "text": "### Why Intact Proteins Are Absent",
            "claim_type": "filler",
            "metadata": {
              "classifier_strategy_version": "react-v7-schema-salvage-markdown-anchor",
              "classifier_round": 0,
              "classifier_stage": "initial"
            }
          },
          {
            "start": 36,
            "end": 145,
            "text": "Protein–metal equilibria are inherently difficult to characterize with classical stability constants because:",
